<article>

  <p>
    Everyday language works. Names buy groceries, settle debts, keep appointments,
    and warn someone that the stove is hot. The same language, pressed without
    care into the deepest questions of the path, can harden into the very
    confusion the path is meant to loosen — a permanent owner, a solid world of
    independent things, a self that must be defended or improved forever.
  </p>

  <p>
    Later Buddhist thought names a remedy that is easy to misuse: two truths.
    Not two competing cosmologies. Two registers of speech and analysis —
    conventional and ultimate — that can both be right for what they are doing.
    The distinction is not a license to say nothing matters. It is a way to keep
    functional language from becoming metaphysical ownership, and liberating
    analysis from becoming a weapon against ethics.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Why the Distinction Arises</h2>

  <p>
    A shopping list and a liberation teaching do not fail in the same way. The
    list fails when the milk is left behind. The teaching fails when words that
    work for persons, actions, and consequences get treated as proof that a
    lasting self sits at the center of experience — or, in the opposite panic,
    when insight into non-ownership is used to erase the persons, actions, and
    consequences altogether.
  </p>

  <p>
    Commentarial and Madhyamaka vocabularies answer that double failure with a
    split that is pragmatic before it is ornate. Speech that tracks persons,
    roles, and causal stories can be true
    <em>as conventional talk</em>. Analysis that refuses intrinsic essence —
    or, in a Pali-primary idiom, refuses to treat any aggregate as a permanent
    owner — can be true
    <em>as ultimate talk</em>. The point is not that ordinary life is a lie.
    The point is that ordinary grammar, left unexamined, tends to smuggle in a
    metaphysics the path does not need.
  </p>

  <p>
    This site’s primary lens remains the early discourses:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span>,
    <a href="/concepts/paticca-samuppada/"><span class="pali" data-pali="paṭicca-samuppāda" data-en="dependent origination">paṭicca-samuppāda</span></a>,
    the aggregates, the path. Two-truths language is a later map of a problem
    those texts already force: how to speak carefully without freezing the
    map into a new self. Hold it lightly.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Conventional Truth</h2>

  <p>
    In Pali commentarial usage, conventional truth —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammuti-sacca" data-en="conventional truth">sammuti-sacca</span>
    — is the register in which persons, tables, and “I went to the market”
    remain intelligible. Sanskrit Madhyamaka often says
    <em>saṃvṛti-satya</em>: truth that covers, or truth that functions under
    the conventions of ordinary designation. The English word
    <em>conventional</em> can sound dismissive. It should not. It names speech
    that works — including the speech of ethics.
  </p>

  <p>
    Without this register, the path collapses. Restraint needs agents who can
    refrain. Compassion needs beings who can suffer. Teaching needs listeners
    who can misunderstand and then understand. Causality itself — intention
    bearing fruit, speech shaping trust, greed thickening the mind — is tracked
    in conventional terms long before anyone opens a treatise on emptiness.
  </p>

  <p>
    The five precepts, right speech, and the daily work of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sīla" data-en="virtue; ethical conduct">sīla</span>
    do not wait for a finished ontology. They assume that harm is harm, that
    apology is owed, that a promise can be kept or broken. That is not naive
    metaphysics. It is the grammar of a life that can be trained.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Ultimate Truth</h2>

  <p>
    Ultimate truth —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paramattha-sacca" data-en="ultimate truth">paramattha-sacca</span>
    in commentarial Pali;
    <em>paramārtha-satya</em> in Sanskrit — is not a loftier story about the
    same solid persons. It is the analysis that withholds intrinsic essence, or
    withholds the status of permanent self, from what convention names so
    readily.
  </p>

  <p>
    Frames differ. Abhidhamma-leaning commentarial speech often parses
    experience into momentary dhammas and refuses to grant ultimate status to
    “person” as a further entity. Madhyamaka emptiness speech —
    <a href="/concepts/emptiness/"><span class="pali" data-pali="suññatā" data-en="emptiness">suññatā</span></a>
    /
    <em>śūnyatā</em> — presses further: even those phenomena lack a private
    nature that would make them what they are from their own side. A
    Pali-primary practitioner need not convert schools to use the practical
    point shared across both: careful looking does not find a lasting owner,
    and clinging to apparent solids manufactures
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ultimate analysis is medicine for reification. It is not a replacement for
    the shopping list. When it works, the mind stops treating “me,” “mine,” and
    “this solid thing” as more than they can bear under scrutiny — without
    needing to pretend that pain, pleasure, and consequence never appeared.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How the Distinction Fails</h2>

  <p>
    Three failure modes show up quickly once the vocabulary is learned.
  </p>

  <p>
    Relativism: “If everything is conventional, nothing is true, so nothing
    matters.” That is a collapse, not a reading. Conventional truth is still
    truth of a kind — speech that tracks consequences. A broken promise remains
    a broken promise in the register that cares about trust. Ultimate analysis
    does not delete the friction; it changes how tightly a center owns it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Denial: “Pain isn’t real; the person isn’t real; ethics is for beginners.”
    This mistakes emptiness or non-self for annihilation. The early texts do
    not teach that contact never occurs. They teach that contact is
    conditioned, and that ownership of it is a habit, not a discovery.
    Unpleasant feeling can be known as unpleasant without being promoted into a
    permanent victim-self — and without being waved away as a dream one need
    not meet.
  </p>

  <p>
    Weaponized ultimate: using “from the ultimate side” to dodge apology,
    excuse harm, or sneer at precepts. That move turns liberating analysis into
    a
    <span class="pali" data-pali="diṭṭhi" data-en="view">diṭṭhi</span>
    with a better costume. The
    <a href="/suttas/alagaddupama/">Alagaddūpama Sutta</a>
    already warns that a teaching grasped by the wrong end becomes a snake that
    bites the holder. Ultimate talk is not exempt.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      Suppose a person needing a raft were to gather grass, sticks, and foliage,
      bind them into a raft, and cross to safety — then think, “This raft has
      been so helpful; I should carry it on my head as I walk on.” Would that
      person be doing what ought to be done with a raft?
    </p>
    <cite>— MN 22, Alagaddūpama Sutta (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>Switching Registers on Purpose</h2>

  <p>
    Practice use is deliberate switching, not permanent residence in one
    altitude. Buying milk: conventional. Noticing the craving that turned a
    delayed package into a personal insult: ultimate analysis applied to the
    ownership habit. Apologizing after harsh speech: conventional again —
    because responsibility lives there. Seeing that “the one who apologized”
    is not a lasting core either: ultimate again, without canceling the apology.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href="/concepts/dual-and-non-dual/">Dual and non-dual maps</a>
    sit nearby. Training speech stays dual for a long time — a mind knowing an
    object, a practitioner cultivating a quality. Non-dual and ultimate talk
    become useful when they loosen the split without dissolving accountability.
    Sequence matters. Premature “nothing is happening / no one is here” often
    decorates avoidance. Lived contact with
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span>
    makes the same words readable.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href="/suttas/sammaditthi/">Right view</a>
    in operation already models this care: it can speak of beings, kamma, and
    fruits in the conventional register, and still refuse a permanent self as
    the owner of that process. Whether rebirth and long-range kamma are
    ultimately settled metaphysics can remain open. Living
    <em>as if</em> intentional action bears fruit — including beyond a single
    afternoon — still tightens speech and restraint now. The payoff arrives in
    this life either way.
  </p>

  <p>
    The two truths are a raft for crossing a particular confusion: how both
    registers can be true without relativism, denial, or a throne called
    “ultimate.” Use them to keep language honest. Put them down when they
    become a new identity. What matters is whether attention returns to
    contact, feeling, and the construction of a center — and whether ethics
    stays answerable while that looking continues.
  </p>

</article>
